column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 21:00 HOURS ON 01/06/2012 A UNIVERSAL PRESSURE PUMPING DRIVER LEFT OUR FACILITY IN MIDLAND TX HEADED TO A WELLSITE IN ASPERMONT TX WITH FOUR THOUSAND GALLONS OF SEVEN AND A HALF PERCENT HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN A BULK TRAILER, AT APPROXIMATELY 23:25 HOURS OUR DRIVER FAILED TO NEGOTITATE AN UPCOMING TURN IN THE ROADWAY AT FM 57 AND SH 70 APPROXIMATELY EIGHTEEN MILES NORTH OF SWEETWATER TX. OUR DRIVER THEN VEERED OFF OF THE ROADWAY AT THE CORNER INTO A LARGE UNHABITED FIELD RESULTING IN THE OVERTURNING OF THE UNIT. AS THE UNIT SLID TO A STOP THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION ON TOP OF THE TANK DUG INTO THE RECENTLY PLOWED FIELD CAUSING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VENT TO BE BROKEN OFF OF DOME LID LEAVING AN OPEN HOLE OF APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES IN DIAMETER, CAUSING ABOVE SAID AMOUNT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY, AND UNIVERSAL PRESSURE PUMPING IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED EAGLE SWS OUT OF FORT WOTH TX TO CLEAN, REMEDIATE AND REPLACE DAMAGED SOIL DUE TO THE SPILL. column168: A Clean Venture Inc. (CVI) 20 cubic yard roll off container was being dropped in a storage area at Ross Incineration Service’s yard. The material was shipped as a solid. During transportation, liquid separated from the material. When the container was tipped up, approximately 2 gallons of sludge spilled over the top of the rear end of the roll off container. The operation was stopped and the CVI driver was instructed to drop the roll off in a contained area. An absorbent berm was placed in the secure drop area and approximately 20 gallons of sludge spilled out of the rear of the container when it was staged.   All of the spilled material was solidified with clay absorbent and disposed of as planned with the original waste material.
column169: Clean Venture gives annual training to drivers and incorporates accident and incident information to prevent reoccurrences. This incident will be included in our annual review. The material was inspected prior to shipment and there was no reason to expect its consistency to change during transportation.

column168: The drums were being offloaded from a Veolia service truck onto a van trailer at the Veolia, Richmond, VA facility by employees through the use of hand drum carts. During the offloading/loading process a small stream of liquid material was noticed by the employees performing the job. The employees reacted quickly, discovered the leaking container, controlled the leak by placing the drum onto its side and then overpacked the container into a metal overpack. The leaking container released approximately 2 gallons of material onto the floor of the trailer and some dripped to the ground below. All spill materials were cleaned up by trained in-house Veolia personal, and properly placed into approved DOT containers for disposal. During the incident investigation by the employees it was discovered that there was a metal weld on the floor of the trialer which was raised from surface of the floor. The weld caught the bottom chime of the drum causing it to bend/tear causing the leak.
column169: To prevent reoccurence in the future, the Veolia employees will check ALL trailers for sharp objects that may cause damage to containers which will be loaded onto the trailers. The employees will make necessary corrections/repairs to the trailers to ensure there are no sharp objects that could damaage the containers.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, icy road conditions caused the Steffey Transport, Inc. vehicle to jackknife, which ruptured the first compartment of the tank truck. Approximately 2,700 gallons of diesel fuel were released.  The Kentucky State Police responded to assess the site.  Diesel fuel had released to the asphalt roadway and soil adjacent to the road shoulder.  Eco-Tech USA, LLC of London, Kentucky was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Eco-Tech USA LLC applied absorbent material to the free liquid along the affected roadway, and recovered the free product.  Absorbent boom was placed within nearby storm drains, as a precautionary measure, to prevent migration.  Site was secured, pending inspection during regular daylight hours.  Upon further investigation of site the following day, diesel fuel was detected within soils adjacent to shoulder.  No evidence of diesel fuel was present within the storm drains, and no water was affected.  Jason Taylor, KYEMA inspector, also inspected site, and confirmed storm drains were not affected, and no state waters were impacted by the release.  Upon receipt of applicable permits and utility locates, Eco-Tech USA, LLC excavated the impacted soils and restored site to preexisting condition.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: Steffey Transport, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: At 1445 hours on january 13,2012 I was notifed by Director of Mechanical Maintenance that he observed product leaking down the sides of tank car TILX 270346 on track 57 at PTRA North Yard. I arrived on scene at 1505 hours and investigated the cause of the leak. Product was visible around the manway cover and one bolt was less than tool tight.  Chemtrec was notifed at 1516 in order to notify the shipper of the release. After obtaining permission to use a local ER crew for the remediation M&M Protection was called to the scene. M&M arrived at 1620 hours and inspected the car. They opened the manway and obsereved that the manway gasket was not installed prior to shipment of the tank car.  They installed a new gasket, closed and sealed the manway.  They then cleaned the tank exterior with a solvent and high pressure water solution. They bio-remediated a small amount of product on the railroad ties and ballast (several small drops).  The scene was cleared at 1734 hours and the car was released to continue to destination.
column169: Chevron was notified of the incident and is investigating the shipper to determine who loaded and secured the tank car for transport.

column168: Clean Harbors Caribe, Inc. accepted a shipment of hazardous waste for transportation to a fully licensed waste management facility. During the course of  the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage facility in order to consolidate less than a truck load quantities onto a single  transport vehicle for continued transportation. While in storage pending continued transportation, an inspection of the containers identified that one individual container had failed allowing material to escape onto the floor of the trailer and asphalt dock area. Facility personnel assembled a response team and after donning appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer. Upon further inspection, it was discovered that the container failed on the contaners body. The response team repackaged remaining product into suitable 5 gallon container and used a chemically compatible absorbent material to absorb all free liquids. This material, along with materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into a suitable UN rated container.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. It is believed that during storage due to temperature change pressure built up in the container causing the head pressure to burp the air out of the container causing a vacuum and the body to fail. As a precaution, all of the liquids were transferred into new 5 gallon pails

column168: A rolloff truck carrying a loaded intermodal box arrived at the intended waste disposal facility where it was noticed to be leaking from underneath.  It was driven to the containment area where it was sampled for immediate entry into the plant. A response crew was notified who donned the appropriate personal protective equipment. Abosrbent pads were placed underneath to catch the dripping material.  When the testing was completed on the sample, the absorbent pads were colleted and placed into the box.  The shipment then proceeded into the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The spill was initially felt to be rainwater as it was raining heavily at the time.  A small amount of material was found to be on the ground then so it was treated as a release.  After emptying the box, a hole was found in the floor of the box.  It was taken out of service and taken to the maintenance department for repairs.  The box should not have been loaded in that condition by the shipper.  The delivering driver should have noticed the hole and had the box repaired prior to delivering it to the customer.

column168: Load was ordered incorrectly. We have an order to deliver on Saturday and we delivered in the correct time frame. Driver arrived and no one was at location. The tank is equipped with an overfill alarm system however, that also is either not working properly or is disconnected. Driver connected delivery hose and started to pump the load. Approx. 2100 gals. was delivered when tank overflowed.Driver immedeiatly shut pump down and used absorbent "snakes" to contain spill.
column169: Customer has put a lock on the fill so no one can deliver during off hours. Reinforced with driver that under no cicumstances should a delivery be made without first acqiring a proper measurement.

Absorbent floor dry generated from the spill clean up was placed into an open head drum and will be managed as hazardous waste.
column169: Reiterate the importance of safe forklift operation while handling containers of hazardous materials/hazardous waste with the Material Handlers at the facility.

column168: WHILE EMPLOYEES WERE SORTING PACKAGES IN THE UPS PHILADELPHIA HUB ON HOG ISLAND ROAD, THEY HEARD A LOUD NOISE AND SAW FIRE COMING FROM A PACKAGE ON A MOVING CONVEYOR BELT. THE EVACUATION ALARM WAS ACTIVATED AND 911 CALLED. THE AREA WAS CLEANED OF PACKAGE HANDLERS AND A P.E. DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE WITH A HAND-HELD FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITHIN 10 MINUTES. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. DAMAGE WAS LIMITED TO 6 OTHER PACKAGES AND 2 CONVEYOR BELTS.  EMPLOYEEES WERE ALLOWED BACK IN THE AREA WITHIN 30 MINUTES. THE OUTSIDE PACKAGING CONTAINING THE AEROSOLS WAS DESTROYED BY THE FIRE, BUT THE HUB PERSONNEL ARE CONFIDENT THAT IT WAS A GROUND SERVICE PACKAGE. AT LEAST ONE OF THE AEROSOLS WITHIN THE PACKAGE WAS BADLY DENTED, SUGGESTING THAT IT HAD RELEASED ITS PROPELLANT, WHICH IN TURN WAS IGNITED BY A STATIC SPARK.

column168: On 1/04/2012 at 1235 hours  personnel at the CSXT Parsons Terminal in Columbus, OH, discovered BRAX 8742, a loaded, covered hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the center hopper at a weld seam on the B end, right side. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, Ohio EPA, and the NRC were notified via CHEMTREC report 2012-01-04-00122. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and cleaned up the spilled material. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Virgil Fowler 706-564-8423. CSXT Mechanical personnel used a patching material to seal the small weld seam fracture. The leak was secured and after verification from the Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) that movement approval was not required, the car was released for transport.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is not required for this incident.    NARRI cause code: 649  2 x (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24

column168: Consignee unloaded 5,800 gallons of product at their plant. Driver left and drove approx 6.7 miles in ~ 15 minutes when tank trailer imploded. Driver called 911 and instigated Carriers Contingency plan. Upon inspection of the tank trailer it was determined that the weld in the trailer shell immediately aft of the upper coupler had seperated due to vacuum inside the trailer. Upon further inspection the next day, the vacuum relief valve was occluded with solid hexamethylene (freeze point ~ 84 degrees F. One speculative theory is that this plug existed prior to off loading preventing make-up gas (nitrogen) from entering tank and releiving vacuum. Other possibility is that valve failed mechanicially. Being investigated.
column169: Implement policy of inspecting pressure relief valves (PRV's) after each load of product shipped at temperature elevated above ambient.

column168: On January 18, 2012 at approximately 10:57 AM, our driver Bernie Kave with Allmine Trucking LLC had just loaded hot asphalt coating at Allmine Paving LLC in Inwood, WV, had traveled from the plant at 200 Development Drive, Inwood, WV (MM #8 off of I-81) to mile marker 20 northbound on I-81 and noticed a rough ride from the trailer.  Bernie Kave exited at mile marker 20, through the intersection and pulled over on the paved shoulder of the on-ramp at exit #20 (northbound I-81).    When checking for the rough ride of the trailer that he later determined was a deflated suspension air bag, he notice a small puddle (approximately 12” in diameter) of coating forming under the trailer near the ladder rack on the passenger side.  He observed a small hole in the outer skin of the insulated tanker about the size of a pencil hole that the coating was coming from.  He immediately obtained the spill kit from his tractor and contained the spill which grew to approximately 16” in diameter and no more than ¼” thick.      Due to the colder outside temperature, the small pencil sized hole created its own seal and stopped the leak.  Bernie Kave and his supervisor (Bert Nichols) then used the spill kit in the tractor to remove the product from the shoulder for proper disposal.    The unit was then dispatched on to final destination in Frederick, MD to TAMKO Building Products, Inc. wherein it was determined that further material had leaked between the outer skin and the inner tank.  This material was contained on site at the plant in Frederick, MD during the unloading process.    Allmine Trucking LLC contracted with Baltimore Tank and had the outer skin removed from the tank and a full inspection revealed that prior to owning this tank trailer, a previous owner had cleaned the tank using some sort of mechanical device (air chisel) and had damaged the tank internally (from the inside out) thus creating several damaged areas on the interior of the tank.  Allmine Trucking LLC had previously had this tank cleaned on the 30th of December, 2011 with high pressure water.  This was the first load of coating that was hauled in the tank since being cleaned.  The old coating removed by the high pressure water uncovered the previously damaged areas and allowed the tank to leak on January 18, 2012.  Baltimore Tank also indicated that corrosion that has occurred between the outer skin/insulation and the exterior of the tank, combined with the air chisel damage from the inside cleaning both contributed to the leak in this tank.
column169: Allmine Trucking LLC has placed this particular tank trailer out of service until it can either be properly repaired or replaced.  Allmine Trucking LLC will have the other tanks in its fleet inspected for any previous damage and will also have any new or used equipment purchased in the future subject to a pre-buy inspection, capable of detecting any structural integrity issues with this type of equipment.

A van trailer containing various shipments of hazardous waste was taken to a trailer repair facility for placard bracket replacement.  During the process, the mechanic drilled a hole through the side of the trailer piercing a drum inside the trailer.  The driver placed a spill pad underneath the trailer and a response crew was notified.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, they entered the trailer and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container. The trailer floor was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and this along with the abosorbent pad was placed into the salvage container.  The trailer then continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver took it upon himself to take the loaded trailer to the repair facility.  He was instructed not to take loaded trailers to repair facilities without approval from his supervisor.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at customer location proceeding to offload product, a leak was discovered from the tank trailer.  Free product was detected on the concrete surface beneath the trailer.  The West Hartford Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Environmental Services, Inc. (ESI) of South Windsor, Connecticut was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free product was detected on the concrete surface and soils adjacent to the customer lot.  ESI applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid, and secured the affected area.  ESI proceeded to offload the damaged tanker into the storage tank at customer facility.  ESI returned to the site the following day to excavate impacted soils, and restore site to preexisting condition.  Waste was transported off site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: NTSB File - DCA012FR002, Westville, IN  On January 6, 2012 at 1420 hours EST, a collision of three westbound trains took place at milepost BI 224.5. Standing Train #1 K68303, a unit train of 77 residue ethanol tank cars on main track #2, was struck in the rear by Striking Train #2 Q39506, a general merchandise freight train consisting of 60 railcars, derailing and blocking both main tracks. Intermodal Train #3 Q16105, westbound on main track #1 ran into the derailed cars. TILX 198139 the 77th, rear car on track #2 was derailed and heavily damaged by Striking Train #2 Q39506, locomotive CSXT 517 + IC 2464.  TILX 198139 was found on the north side of the impact area, both head sections severely dented. A-end head was dented; 104 inches across, 83 inches in height and 29 inches in depth. Tthe tank pad at the base of the head was torn above the head block weld, with a tear in the tank head material 12 inches in length and 6 inches across.The impact from the locomotive pushed the stub sill downward, causing a longitudinal tear next to the stub sill approximately 4 inches on each side.   The B-end was bent down in a 90 degree angle, a dent in the lower half of the tank head section measuring 110 inches across, 72 inches in height and 40 inches in depth and   three small dents above midline.  Damage assessment was conducted by a team from the FRA and CSX HazMat. Chemtrec report 20120106-00163. There was a general public evacuation of 54 people, duration 4 hours.  Cause code: H605  Failure to comply with restricted speed in connection with the restrictive indication of a block or interlocking signal  ATARI: 5(4+3)(2+4)=75
column169: NTSB File - DCA012FR002, Westville, IN  On January 7, 2012 at 0001 hours, CSX Transportation's Safety Department effected a Safety Stand Down for 72 hours listing critical operating rules.

column168: After plant personnel loaded the truck with 10 pallets (40 drums), the independent driver set load locks in place to secure the drums, gathered the paperwork, and exited the plant around 9:30 am.  At 9:50 am, the driver called the plant operator to report that he saw product leaking from the trailer and that he was on his way back to the plant.  After the driver returned to the plant, product was found on the floor of the trailer.  Absorbent was applied to the spill area and the trailer was unloaded.  At pallet number 6, a puncture measuring approximately 1.5” by .5” was discovered about 4” from the bottom of a drum, and the trailer’s metal side wall was torn, with metal protruding from the side wall at a location corresponding to where the punctured drum was found.  Product above the puncture point had leaked from the drum.  Absorbent was applied to the spilled product in the truck, and it was scooped up and put into drums for proper disposal.  The outside of the trailer was wiped with rags, which were properly handled and disposed of.  The trailer was then sent to Qualawash to be washed inside and outside of the trailer.
column169: A 1/4/2012 Root Cause Report and investigation identified a need for improved inspection procedures prior to loading.  A more effective inspection method will be implemented.  In addition, poor lighting may have been a factor in the incident; high-powered spot lights have been ordered to improve lighting in the trailer-loading area.  An evaluation is planned of the procedures in place for transportation incidents when the plant is notified of an emergency.  Improvements and training will be performed as necessary so that operators may instruct drivers to follow proper spill response procedures.  We will also review this incident and changes in procedures in safety meetings throughout the plant.

column168: Driver reported that car had swerved in front of him, applied brakes then exited road. This caused driver to brake excessively to avoid hitting car. Truck was carrying 11 IBCs of ferric chloride and 3 of caustic soda.Truck is a 10 wheel straight truck with flat bed and permanent side rails. Load was set back one pallet space from front of trailer to distribute weight off of steering axle. In front of load was a load bar attached to rails of trailer acting as the bulkhead of load. When brakes were applied, bar broke when 2 totes of ferric moved forward about 10 inches. One tote received a small (less than 1/2 inch) puncture/crack at corner of tank producing a steady seeping of product. Driver stopped truck at first safe place (about 1/2 mile) to inspect load and discovered leaking IBC. Seeping continued for approximately 2 hours while response team traveled to site and performed clean up. Driver applied, absorbent pads and 'pigs' to contain spilled material while waiting for response team. Approximately 5 gallons was lost. Response was by Brenntag personnel. Material was transferred from leaking IBC to new IBC, trailer floor cleaned, all contaminated dirt gathered and removed. Load was secured against further movement. The RQ (1,000 Ibs) was not reached.
column169: Review of the incident revealed that the temporary bulkhead was insufficient to prevent forward movement of cargo in an emergency braking event. All the IBCs loaded on this truck had galvanized steel frames. The truck bed is steel, resulting in metal on metal which contributed to the IBCs being more likely to move. The load bar was placed near the upper third of the IBCs with no blocking at the floor. Corrective action is to (1) add a second load bar at the floor against the IBCs and (2) place empty pallets on the floor between the truck bulkhead and the floor mounted load bar for additional load securement. The new configuration for this type load will be pallets on the floor against the truck bulkhead. A load bar flush against the pallets on the floor and attached to the side rails. The IBCs loaded flush against the floor mounted load bar with a second load bar against the upper third of the 2 IBCs at front of the load. We believe this will prevent forward movement in a similar hard braking event.

Plan of action, to allow product to harden, and return to site to recover released product.  Free product was contained within the median, and did not threaten to impact waters of the state.  Upon receipt of applicable permits and utility locates, OSI Environmental returned to the site, and recovered the released product from within the median. Confirmation samples were pulled to confirm all residual product was removed. There were no injuries or exposures reported. ON 1/10/2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30PM THE DMO TANKWAGON DRIVEN BY JEAN CHARLES MONEL WAS PROCEEDING NORTH ON RT. 13 IN PRINCESS ANNE TRANSPORTING APPROXIMATELY 700 GAL OF KEROSENE. THE DMO VEHICLE WAS DRIVING IN THE RIGHT LANE. AS HE PROCEEDED THROUGH THE CONTROLLED INTERSECTION OF RT. 13 AND MT. VERNON ROAD A VEHICLE APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION FROM WEST MT. VERNON ROAD RAN THE RED TRAFFIC SIGNAL MAKING CONTACT WITH THE DRIVER SIDE REAR QUARTER OF THE DMO VEHCLE CAUSING IT TO SPIN AND ROLL ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE. THE DMO VEHICLE, DRAGGING VEHICLE #2, THAN SLID APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET COMING TO REST IN THE LEFT LANE OF RT. 13 NORTH. THE DMO VEHICLE TANK SPLIT AND CAUGHT FIRE. VEHICLE #2 WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE BURNING DMO VEHICLE BY AN UNKNOWN PASSING MOTORIST WITH A PICKUP AND A TOW ROPE.  AS FLAMES BEGAN TO SPREAD THROUGH THE CABIN, DRIVER JEAN CHARLES MONEL KICKED OUT THE DRIVER SIDE WINDOW AND CRAWLED OUT OF THE VEHICLE. DRIVER MONEL WAS NOT ABLE TO WALK. TWO PEDESTRIANS PULLED DRIVER MONEL FROM THE BURNING VEHICLE TO SAFETY. DRIVER MONEL WAS TRANSPORTED TO PENINSULA GENERAL HOSPITAL. THE PRELIMINARY DIAGNOSIS IS A CRACKED 5TH VERTEBRAE AND A BRUISED KIDNEY. HE WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL LATE TUESDAY NIGHT.  THE CONDITION OF THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME. CPL. ROBERT SMITH STATED THAT HER INJURIES DID NOT APPEAR TO BE SERIOUS.  CPL. ROBERT SMITH OF THE PRINCESS ANNE POLICE DEPARTMENT 410-651-1822 STATED THAT HE INTERVIEWED THREE WITNESSES. THE THREE WITNESSES STATE THAT VEHICLE #2 RAN THE RED SIGNAL. WE WILL OBTAIN A POLICE REPORT WITHIN 7 DAYS.  DRIVER MONEL STATED THAT THE RED LIGHT WARNING FLASHER APPROXIMATELY A QUARTER MILE SOUTH OF RT. 13 WAS NOT FLASHING WHEN HE PASSED IT.  THE DMO VEHICLE IS LOCATED AT SIMPSON TOWING IN SALISBURY.  THERE WAS A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 700 GAL. OF KEROSENE. MOST OF THE KEROSENE BURNED IN THE ACCIDENT. KEN RUSS IS MEETING WITH MDE ON THURSDAY 1/12/2012.

The tank car was observed to be leaking lading from the bottom of the jacketed tank. Further inspection indicated that lading was leaking from an unseen defect in the tank as the jacket was obscuring the actual point of release.  The car was isolated at the UPRR Lake Charles yard and a small containment pool was established to collect the lading. The shipper dispatched a vacuum truck and removed an estimated 170 gallons of remaining product and the containment was monitored for several days until no further leakage was observed. The shipper is to obtain movement approval for repairs.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED THIS MORNING, (1-17-2012), TO HAVE LOST ONE OF THREE ITEMS FROM THE PACKAGE TWO DAYS AFTER IT HAD BEEN DELIVERED IN AMARILLO, TX ON JANUARY 14. SEARCHES WERE DONE IN MEMPHIS, TN, LUBBOCK, TX, AND AMARILLO, TX IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE CALL CAME IN. AS WE WERE DISCUSSING THE INCIDENT WITH EACH OF THOSE LOCATIONS, ANOTHER CALL WAS MADE BY THE FEDEX OVERGOODS DEPARTMENT TO THE MEM HUB OPERATIONS SPILL OFFICE OF SOME CONTENTS THAT HAD BEEN LOCATED. THE CONTENTS WERE PICKED UP AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THIS WAS THE MISSING ITEM OF TL-201. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE CONTENTS WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM BACK TO THE ORIGIN. THERE WAS NO EXPOSURES TO ANY EMPLOYEE AND NOTHING WAS CRACKED OR DAMAGED. THE BOX HAD BEEN COMPROMISED, (TORN AND THE INNER PIG HAD FALLEN OUT) AND WAS APPARENTLY  RETAPED UNKNOWING THAT ANYTHING HAD FALLEN OUT, AND WAS MOVED ON FOR DELIVERY.

column168: After tank car NATX 37001 was spotted to a repair track in the railyard for a truck side frame defect, a mechanical carman reported a small amount of leaked product on its upper side shell emanating from the top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected NATX 37001 and reported the leak source was at the base of the threaded 3 inch liquid valve. On 1/05/2012, contract responders secured the liquid valve that was 2 full turns loose on its threaded connections.  All other fittings were inspected and found secure. Spillage on NATX 37001's tank shell was wiped. No further product release was observed during subsequent movements within the railyard.   Intact valve housing cover seal removed was numbered 1271074  0004097 and replaced with seal numbered 000497.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securemnent and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Hazchem personnel transfered the product to a new tote and performed the necessary remediation activities.

A tanker loaded with hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  While being inspected at the gate, a small drip was noticed coming from the rear valve.  The trailer was moved to a containment area and a response crew was summoned.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, they attempted to stop the leak.  The leak could not be stopped, the spilled area on the ground was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material and the trailer was taken into the incinerator for immediate offloading.
column169: After unloading, the trailer was taken to the maintenance facility for repair or replacement of the vertical flange on the rear valve.  The trailer showed no signs of leaking at the time of pickup or during a routine load check performed by the driver while enroute.

A BNSF mechanical responder inspected GATX 51969 reporting that the reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) atop GATX 51969 was the odor source. column168: EE #504245, Osvaldo Luzcando notified us of a possible undeclared package in the station. the shipment had been refused intially by the recipient and was returned to the Fedex office. He advised of Diesel fuel markings on the outer packaging but no shippers declaration or haz marking/labeling otherwise. He was advised to open the package upon which 2 containers labeled diesel fuel were discovered. CAS68334-30-5. a probable MSDS was obtained via website www.msds.exxonmobil.com which initially listed the product as class 3/flammable liquid UN1202. The shipper, Jennifer Strickland/Ken Hurtzberg were contacted by phone and advised Jan 18, 1000CST. They advised this MSDS was not correct, further that an original MSDS should be with the freight. The fedex agent subsequently faxed a copy that omitted section 14. The flash point of this document was 147Ff which does not qualify as flammable liquid. The fedex agent adv Jan 19 that he had inadvertently not faxed the entire doc. Entire MSDS received Jan 19/section 14 notes shipment Class 9/UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substance."
column169: Shipper was initially advised that the package did not qualify as a flammable liquid Jan 18. Shipper was re-advised after subsequent receipt of section 14 of original MSDS (fax) that it did however qualify as Class 9/Un3080 and was considered undeclared DG, and a 5800 would be filed.

column168: On 1/31/12 at 2259 hrs., CSXT personnel in Anderson, IN., discovered PROX 41840, a loaded tank car of Propylene Tetramer, leaking from the manway area. The car was in train Q21931 and the shipper, Imperial Oil Products LTD, was notified. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 4 of 8 manway bolts less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Don Willis, at 403-809-2976. Contractor personnel checked for gasket alignment and secured the manway bolts.  A new security seal was installed and the car was released for transport.    Cause Code:  200                                      NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) =  60

column168: The driver lee johnson was at the new town railyard unloading the truck. When the loader operating the railcar noticed the product was coming out the discarge line .The loader told the driver to stop the offload so he could fix the leak when it was fixed he told driver to continue the pumping they notice that a valve was closed so it backflushed the system back on the truck it hit the pressure of the pto and pop the line off of the top of the pto which in  turn led to the discharge of product onto the ground there was approximate 2 to 3 barrels drop on the ground. there was about 1 to 2 minutes of discharge of product. the driver was able to close fire valves and stop the flow of oil.
column169: There should be a more precise communication between the loader and driver and a better training for drivers and loaders and a better safety plan in place for the release of product in the event of an accidential discharge so there would be a quicker response to the scene. We as the carrier will see to it that are training for are drivers and we as acompany will do a better job so we do not have a spill in the future.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Notified that TILX 270275, load Petroleum Crude Oil, Class 3, PG I, was discovered leaking from a loose manway cover and defective deteriorated manway nozzle gasket. KCS responded to this incident with subcontractor USES and replaced manway gasket and closed manway tool tight. The exterior of the tank car was decon. The car was then released to destination.    File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Driver arrived at customer location for a pickup with seven drums of hazardous materials secured in the nose of the trailer (from earlier pickup).  The trailer also contained a long piece of sheet metal (approx 14ft), which was secured (by strap) along the trailer wall four to six feet from the hazm  at shipment.  Upon arriving at the customer location, the driver inspected the trailer and verified that the shipments were all still secured and did not discover any problems with the freight.  The customer began loading pallets into the trailer (while being observed by the driver, who notified the   customer of the metal located along the side of the trailer).  On the last pallet, the customer caught the freight on the earlier loaded sheet metal, moving it significantly forward.  The driver says at that point fluid was heard leaking and then visually flowing out of the trailer (from being punc  tured by the sheet metal).
column169: More careful loading by the customer would likely have prevented this occurance.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: There was a large bundle of steel poles that were put up right next to the hazardous pallets. With the extended trip over the rail from South Chicago to San Bernardino the poles punctured the box and the plastic bottle in the box.
column169: Make sure that there is proper blocking and bracing of hazmat. Either put a pallet or extra dunnage between the piping and the hazmat pallet or make sure that the hazmat pallets are put flush against other standard pallets.

column168: On January 16, 2012, R&L Carriers had a poly tote of UN1805 Phosphoric Acid Solution, 8, PG III released approximately 1 quart of material onto the dock of the terminal. It was reported that additional cargo was placed onto the tote causing it to bend, which resulted in a pin hole on the top portion of the tote. R&L Carriers personnel cleaned up the released material. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site on January 17, 2012 to perform a tote transfer. The damaged tote was transported off site for disposal.

Vapor Leak was detected on rear pump seal at Weigh station in Wood County, WV. Following communication with Transportation Division of West Virginia Public Service Commission Officer, the transport MC331 trailer was relocated to Shop where seal and O-ring were replaced. There were no injuries, or off site consequences as a result of this occurrence.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On January 25th at 1447 hours, personnel in the CSXT Holly Hill Yard discovered GATX 22607, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., EPA Manifest #00538288VES, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Veolia Environmental Services was contacted through their emergency response number.  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a continuous leak of liquid being emitted from the re-closing pressure relief device.  The pressure relief device spring was checked and no exceptions were noted.  The cause of the release was determined to be from over pressurization of the container.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the Veolias Transportation Logistics Manager, Tim Ludwig at 732-469-5100.  Contractor personnel off loaded 150 gallons of product and the leak subsided. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  No 7.1 report will be required for this incident.    Cause code: 419   NARRI: 5(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90
column169: Ensure operators leave sufficient outage for product expansion in tank car.

column168: On January 11, 2012, Con-way Safety Department was notified by terminal personnel that a minor amount of toxic solid (1-2 cups) had spilled onto the dock.  The area was isolated to prevent spreading the material and possible contamination.  Con-way Safety contacted ERTS to coordinate corrective action.  The ERTS dispatched BBU to manage a UN2811 toxic solid inorganic methylene release.  BBU personnel arrived on site to investigate the release and began cleanup operations.  The contractor placed the material from the damaged bag into a 95 gallon poly overpack drum.  The contractor utilized absorbents to collect the released material, which was containerized into an overpack drum along with the damaged bag.    Root cause analysis points to improper preparation for transportation.  The body of the bag had been ripped during transportation.  Other freight had been stacked on top of this pallet of bags causing the damage in transit.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While travelling on I-30 west bound near mile marker 86 the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. tractor-tanker unit rolled-over.  As a result of the incident the tanker was damaged and approximately 6200 gallons of material were released.  The free product impacted soil and a nearby creek.  TAS Environmental Services of Little Rock, Arkansas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. deployed absorbent boom to contain the free liquid in the impacted creek.    Between the dates of January 11, 2012 and February 1, 2012 TAS Environmental Services, Inc. recovered approximately 19,000 gallons of contaminated water and 288 cubic yards of contaminated soil.  Additional cleanup is still pending.      The Slay Transportation Co. Inc. driver was a fatality.  The exact cause of death is not known at this time.  The speed of the tractor at the time of the incident is not known at this time.  However Slay Transportation Co. Inc. tractor's are governed at 65mph.
column169: No plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Slay Transportation Co. Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: COACH DOCK ASSOCIATES ON PROPER PROCEDURES.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on I-80 westbound, driver was involved in a single-vehicle accident due to icy road conditions.  Vehicle veered off roadway and rolled over into center median at milemarker 8.  Free product began releasing from the wash out caps on the tank truck.  Pennsylvania DEP, Mercer County OEM, West Middlesex Fire Department, and Pennsylvania DOT responded to assess the site.  One lane of I-80 westbound was closed as a result of the accident.  Weavertown Environmental Group of Carnegie, Pennsylvania was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Linden Bulk Transportation provided an empty trailer for offload of remaining product from the overturned tanker.  Weavertown Environmental Group assisted in product offload, tanker was uprighted, and approximately 40 gallons of free product had released to the soils within the median.  Absorbent pads had been applied to absorb free product, and local responders utilized three (3) 15-gallon drums as containment buckets to catch product while leaking from wash out caps.  Weavertown Environmental Group excavated the impacted soils from within the median and recovered the spent absorbents from the area.  Waste was containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums, along with cleanup debris and virgin product, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: Linden Bulk Transportation, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on I-70 eastbound at milemarker 1.5 in West Alexander, PA, driver was involved in a single-vehicle accident, caused by icy road conditions.  Accident resulted in a rollover, which damaged the bulk tank truck.  The West Alexander Fire Department and Washington County Hazmat Team immediately responded to contain the free liquid within the affected ditchline.  Local responders created a containment dam at the edge-line of the affected ditch, which contained free product to immediate area, pending contractor arrival.  Responders also installed wooden plugs at trailer breach point, which slowed leak.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI) of Washington, Pennsylvania was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  SPSI assisted in upright and recovery of damaged tanker.  Upon removal of damaged vehicle, SPSI utilized a vacuum truck to recover the free product from within the ditchline.  SPSI proceeded to excavate the impacted soils, which were containerized into (4) roll-off containers on site.  Recovery efforts were complete Sunday morning January 22nd at approximately 04:00 EST.  SPSI returned to the site on Monday morning, during regular daylight hours, to further assess contamination.  At this time, snow had melted, which allowed for enhanced observation of further impact.  SPSI proceeded to excavate all visually impacted soils, which were containerized into one (1) additional rolloff box.  Confirmation samples were pulled to confirm all contamination was recovered.  Disposal will be coordinated directly by SPSI in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence of the incident or similar incidents, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend safety meetings.  Safety meetings address such issues as handling spills, driving hazards and job specific training.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend DOT job specific training classes.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. addresses safety issues in their driver's newsletter.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safety guidelines to all drivers and employees.

column168: Tank car UTLX 203303 was reported leaking product from the top fitting area during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and containment buckets were placed under UTLX 203303. A nearby contract hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 203303. The responder reported the sample line valve was in the open position with no closure plug applied (the plug was missing from the end of the plug retention chain). The sample line valve was closed and a suitable closure plug was applied and tool tightened. Also, the magnetic gaging device was found with 3 of 4 of its mounting flange stud bolt nuts not tool tight and these were tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Securement was completed by 2100 hrs. CST, 1/30/2012. All spillage captured in the containment buckets and on the tank shell rapidly evaporated. Valve housing cover's intact seal Stoffel National 49670 was replaced by a BNSF seal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.  UTC was also notified of UTLX 203303's condition following its recent tank qualification in December 2011.

column168: Owner/Operator: Revere Smelting & Refining Corporation Date: January 10, 2012 at 9:40am Location: 84 Lane, near exit 120 of Route 17 and Route 211, Middletown NY While driver was exiting Route 17 at exit 120 he looked in his mirror and saw smoke coming from the flatbed trailer. Upon exiting the ramp he turned onto Route 211 then pulled onto 84 Lane (entrance to Honda of Middletown) and parked his trailer. Driver removed tarp and discovered a fire had started on a pallet of scrap batteries in the nose of the trailer. He attempted to put the fire out with his fire extinguisher but was unsuccessful. Driver then proceeded to call 911 and disconnect the tractor from the trailer and relocate it away from the trailer. Local public emergency responders put out the fire and spread absorbents over the roadway. Route 211 was closed both directions. Area immediately downwind was evacuated (Mobile Gas Station). Responding officials directed Regional Trucking to transport the load of scrap batteries and trailer to Revere's Middletown facility. A hazardous materials response cleanup crew, hired by Revere Smelting & Refining Corporation, cleaned up absorbents and fire suppression material from the roadway upon release of the incident scene by local emergency response officials.
column169: Revere Smelting & Refining Corporation is discontinuing use of flatbed trailers to reduce the potential for metal contact with the load while in transit. In addition, Revere Smelting & Refining Corporation has reviewed packaging requirements with suppliers.

column168: At approximately 0720 hours on 01/17/2012, a driver unloading ethanol from his truck trailer into a terminal steel storage tank noticed product spraying from the line.  A 3/8" nipple on the suction side of the ethanol off-loading pump fractured and caused ethanol to be released from the inbound ethanol line onto the ground.  The 3/8" nipple connected a pressure transmitter to the main ethanol line.  The driver immediately stopped the pump and closed his valve.  He then contacted a terminal employee, alerting him to the issue.  The terminal employee closed down the inbound ethanol line and placed a drip pan under the compromised fitting.  The supervisor was called on the radio who mobilized two vacuum trucks and additional spill response equipment.  A gas meter was monitored to ensure proper vapor control and the area was cordonned off from traffic.  Approximately 100 gallons of ethanol product impacted the concrete spill containment and surrounding road.  All was cleaned up.  The 3/8" nipple connected a pressure transmitter to the main ethanol line.  The nipple and transmitter had been installed years earlier and were not located in the proper location.  The nipple extended out from the line horizontally before connecting with the transmitter.  This put stress on the nipple and the equipment was located on the side of the line instead of on top, exposing it to potential impact from personnel.
column169: 1. A ball valve was installed between the nipple and main line to ensure this location could be better isolated in the event of another similar incident.             2. The nipple and the transmitter were relocated to a point where there was less stress on the nipple and where it was protected from potential impact from personnel.                                                                                                                        3. The nipple replacement was shorter, minimizing this failure point.                    4. An inspection of the terminal was conducted to identify other similar equipment setups.                                                                                                        5. The incident was reviewed with all personnel at the facility to ensure lessons learned were properly disseminated.

column17: UNITED STATES DEPT OF ENERGY RICHLAND dba Pacific Northwest National Laboratory
column168: On Tuesday, January 24, 2012, a shipment of equipment was received by a storage contractor working on behalf of Pacific Northwest National Laboratory in Richland, WA from Bannaker Industries in Rhode Island.  The shipment contained 164 - 3.6 liter He-3 tubes (UN1046), each at 44 psia.  The tubes were both in equipment and not in equipment (i.e., secured within multiple wooden crates).  All materials were packaged as if being shipped under DOT-SP 9880.  The truck driver (Panther Expedited Services) was not able to produce appropriate shipping papers identifying the hazardous material.  There was no impact at the receiving facility.
column169: The shipper (Banneker) was working on behalf of another entity (Raytheon), who knew about the hazardous nature of the material.  It does not appear the shipper had any hazmat employee or shipper training in accordance with DOT requirements.  Although PNNL was not directly involved in the shipment and is difficult for us to know the details of what happened on the other side, it appears to us that Raytheon should have verified shipper working on their behalf had adequate training.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: A BNSF local train crew reported tank car GATX 6311 leaking product at the top fitting area. No spillage was observed impacting the ground. GATX 6311 was cordoned-off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 6311 and reported the leak source was at the liquid line closure cap's threaded connection. GATX 6311 was carefully moved and isolated at a nearby repair track. Further inspection of the closure cap's threaded connection revealed the closure cap appeared tight but was not sealing at its threaded connection.  Responder neutralized the small amount of spillage on the tank shell and removed the closure cap. No thread sealant was observed at the threaded connection.  The responder cleaned the threaded area and applied thread sealant to the threads. The closure cap was reapplied and tool tightened. No further product spillage was observed during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: On 2/01/2012, a meeting with shipper representatives and BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Material was held to discuss recent product releases from the liquid line's closure cap, securement procedures and explore possible solutions to eliminate similar future incidents.

column168: Univar driver picked up 93% sulfuric acid at Rhodia on Wilmington Ave in Long Beach.  After exiting about a 1/4 mile from the facility the driver noticed a drip from his trailer. It was approximately 2:35 pm.  He immediately stopped to investigate and found that the vent valve was left open and product had splashed out.  He ran in to notify Rhodia that he had a spill and needed assistance and also notified Univar dispatch.  Brian Faust in Regulatory was contacted at approximately 2:50 pm and called in the spill to OES at 3:10 pm case # 12-0528. He also contacted ECI to mobilize a spill clean-up team at 3:20 pm. Rhodia personnel helped our driver isolate the area and notified local emergency responders. Prior to isolation a civilian car drove through the spill and stopped in the Rhodia parking lot.  A passenger got out of the car to look under the car for damages and got sulfuric on his right shoulder.  Rhodia personnel immediately got him under a safety shower for 15 minutes.  He refused to go to our clinic and said he would follow-up with his own doctor tomorrow.  He had minor skin surface irritation (no blistering or bubbling).   The car had damage to the paint and was decontaminated by Rhodia personnel.  Vinny Sharma (BOM) sent the driver for a drug/alcohol screen per Univar policy, ensured the clean up by ECI was being handled properly and ensured all Univar policies were followed.
column169: Primary reasons for the incident were;  1. Driver left vent down valve in open position after relieving pressure in the tanker trailer before opening the dome lid to load.  After loading the trailer with sulfuric acid 93%, the trailer was driven which created sloshing of product that leaked out of the vent down valve because the valve was in the open position.    2. Operator Error – did not follow bulk trailer loading procedure pertaining to venting down a trailer and verifying all valves closed prior to driving a trailer. Driver became complacent with filling the inspection form, as he filled this form 2 to 3 times daily.    Safety Committee recommends the following;  1. Utilize Univar checklist for loading and offloading bulk products (OSM 3.13 x 1, Prototype Tank Truck Loading Checklist).  Provide training, document retention plan and periodic audit.   2. Conduct Safety Stand Down (All Hands) meeting at SE Santa Fe Springs branch to review the incident, discuss findings and safety behaviors, action plan to prevent recurrence.   3. Provide re-fresher training for all Bulk and Mini-Bulk drivers at SE Santa Fe Springs branch on HazMat Emergency Response off-site procedure pertaining to the order of steps and priorities for a release:  Evaluate & Protect, Notify, Control & Contain, Clean Up.   4. Evaluate equipment design (valve, switches, hose, etc) on bulk trailers used to perform trailer vent down function.  Eliminate driver decision making to close critical isolation valves  by designing systems with an interlock or mechanical linkage to ensure valve closure prior to moving a bulk tanker trailer.

column168: THE RED ROCK DRIVER AND THE FACILITY LOADER WERE LOADING CRUDE OIL FROM THE TANK TRUCK INTO THE CALL CAR. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT AFTER FILLING THE PREVIOUS RAIL CAR (TRFX 1336) TO THE REQUIRED LEVEL, THE FIRST LOADING STATION CLOSED THE BOV AND THE DRIVER REVERSED HIS PTO PUMP TO SUCK ALL THE REMAINING CRUDE OIL (IN HIS HOSE) BACK INTO HIS TRUCK. ONCE COMPLETED, THE FACILITY LOADER DETACHED THE HOSE FROM THE RAIL CAR AND ASSISTED THE RED ROCK DRIVER WITH PLACING THE HOSE BACK ON THE TRUCK TRAILER. THE DRIVER MOVED AHEAD TO THE NEXT LOADING STATION; HOWEVER; HE DID NOT TURN HIS PTO PUMP BACK TO THE OFF-LOADING POSITION. ONCE THE PUMP WAS STARTED, IT BEGAN TO DRAW CRUDE OIL FROM THE RAIL CAR THEREBY FILLING UP HIS TRAILER. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS FULL, CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED THROUGH THE TRAILER'S VENT LINE.

PLEASE NOTE WE ARE THE FACILITY WHO SUBMITTED THIS REPORT AND THE RELEASE CAME FROM THE CARRIERS TRUCK TRAILER. WE BELIEVE THEY DID NOT FILE THIS REPORT, SO WE FILED ONE.

column168: This shipment was found to be leaking during the sort.  Standard spill procedures were followed and the package was contained in a salvage drum pending final disposition.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While attempting to make a right hand turn, rear wheels went off shoulder, causing the cargo tank to rollover onto road shoulder.  Cargo tank was damaged, resulting in the release of approximately 100 gallons of free product.  Harris County Sheriff’s Department and Waller Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Harris County Sheriff’s Deputy Oldner dispatched the County Hazmat Team to respond to the site.  Garner Environmental Services of Deer Park, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Linden Bulk Transportation Co., Inc. supplied two (2) empty trailers for offload of damaged tanker.  Upon completion of transfer, cargo tank was uprighted and recovered from the site.  Garner Environmental Services, Inc. placed absorbent boom into nearby drainage ditches to prevent migration, and recovered the contaminated soils from the impacted roadside ditch.  Due to heavy rains during recovery efforts, some product had been washed down roadside ditch, and was unrecoverable.  Garner Environmental Services, Inc. worked at the direction of Harris County’s Pollution Control Unit to adequately remediate the affected area.   Post excavation samples were pulled to confirm all residuals had been removed.  Waste was transported to Garner Environmental Services, Inc.’ facility, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Linden Bulk Transportation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column14: I94EB one mile west of 27th St
column168: Driver was heading eastbound on I-94 in the right hand lane.  After going over a ridge at 50 mph he noticed vehicles at a complete stop immediately in front of his truck.  He down shifted to slow down , applied the brakes and needed to change lanes immediately to avoid hitting the stopped cars on the freeway, The driver was unable to control the truck and hit the barrier between the east and west bound lanes striking a light pole and tipping the truck.  The truck blocked the lanes on the freeway and it lost cylinder load.  Approximately 60 cylinders were scattered with three liquid oxygens and one 55# carbon dioxide cylinder venting its product to atmosphere.  The carbon dioxide cylinder lost its protective cap and subsequently lost its valve releasing the product to atmosphere.  The liquid oxygen cylinders protective ring was bent and damaged from impact and damaging the liquid level float and pressure gauge resulting in the release of oxygen to atmosphere. The police reported the accident to have happened approximately 11:15 am and the store was notified approximately 11:30 a.m.  We dispatched two available cylinder trucks to the scene to retrieve the cylinders so that the wrecker could overturn the damaged truck and remove it from obstructing traffic.  Approximately 3:30 p.m the incident was resolved.
column169: No suggestions for improvement

column168: Driver was making a right turn onto State Highway 290. He got the right rear trailer wheels onto a soft shoulder.The shoulder gave way and the rear of the trailer slid into a ditch, caUsing the unit to roll on to its side. Harris County Sheriffs Department, Waller Fire Department, and Harris County Hazmat Team responded to the scene. Carrier contracted with Garner Environmental Services Inc. to perform the clean up. Carrier dispatched a clean tank trailer and two tractors equipped with cargo pumps to affect the product transfer. Once the transfer was completed, the tank was uprighted and towed from the scene back to the Carrier's terminal. Garner Environmental Services placed absorbent booms in the ditch to prevent the migration of the spilled material. Garner Environmental Services worked at the direction of the Harris County Pollution Control Unit to adequately remediate the affected area. Post excavations amples were taken to confirm that all residual had been removed. The waste generated was transported to Garner Environmental Services facility pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported entrained tank car TILX 110390 was emanating a product vapor from the top fitting area along with product wetness on its side shell. TILX 110390 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from contract responders. Responders reported the Sentry Shield security bag surrounding the top valve area was intact and cable sealed. The seal number was unreadable. A detailed inspection revealed that the frangible disc was missing from the Salco Quick Inspect safety vent, as well as, the surge protector that was found outside the safety vent lying atop the valve housing surface. Also, the Quick Inspect top cap/plug was not affixed. The open safety vent orifice allowed product to escape during rail movement. The responders reinstalled the surge protector, a suitable replacement frangible disc and secured the top cap. The Sentry Shield security bag was refitted. Spillage on the tank exterior and observed ground impact area was neutralized.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The shipment of drums was delivered to Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C. (VESTS), West Carrollton, OH on January 24, 2012 by Tonawanda Tank Transport Services (EPA ID# NYD097644801) from Greenville Technology, Inc.  Upon delivery, the drums were offloaded by a VESTS employee.  During the offloading process, the VESTS employee notice that one of the drum lids came off while in transit and a small spill had occurred on the trailer.  The VESTS employee remediated the spilled material and replaced the lid on the drum.  The drum was placed into storage at the Veolia facility and later processed for disposal at that location.      Veolia has notified our customer of the incident in an effort to prevent another occurance.
column169: Veolia was neither the shipper nor transporter of the drums in question.  Veolia only acted as receiver of the materials for disposal.  In an effort to prevent another occurrence of this type, Veolia has notified our customer of the incident.

column168: On January 03, 2012, NALCO Co. consigned DHL for delivery of 20 foot container to Luba Freeport LTD, in Equatorial Guinea.  The container held seven tote tanks; three containing NALCO EC1118A hazardous material UN 2924 (ENERCEPT EC1118A) and four containing non-hazardous material Oceanic HW-525P.  Bill of Lading No. 118953592 was issued for the shipment.      Universal Africa Lines (UAL) had scheduled the container to be shipped onboard their chartered vessel, FLINTERMAR.  The container was stowed, blocked and braced by Unique Carrier Services of Houston, Texas.  The dock receipt indicates that the shipment was received on January 16, 2012.    On January 29, 2012, at 1930 hours, Container DUCU206820-6 was loaded into the No. 2 cargo hold tween deck of the M/V FLINTERMAR as she was berthed at Manchester Terminal, Houston, Texas.    On January 30, 2012, at 1100 hours, the vessel’s crew noticed a strong aromatic odor coming from cargo hold No. 2 and it was found that the container was leaking an oily like substance.  Gulf Stream Stevedores immediately contacted Oil Mop Inc., to conduct the cleanup of the vessel and the container.  The container and cargo hold were de-contaminated through absorption of the spilled compound, ventilation and using a vapor absorbing compound referred to as HIDEAWAY.    The vessel also carrying a cargo of calcium chloride stored in super sacks.  The initial cleanup was not successful because the compound had run underneath the bags of calcium chloride.  After approximately 35 bags of cargo were removed from the vessel, the cleanup was completed on January 31, 2012.       The spill can be attributed to a 3” screw nail being inadvertently driven into   one of the tote tanks containing the ENERCEPT 1118-A compound.  It was determined that the container was not lying perfectly flat in the storage area causing the liquid to run towards the rear of the container.  When the container was placed onboard the vessel it was at a time when the vessel had a slight port list.  Overnight approximately 60 gallons of the ENERCEPT 1118-A leaked out of the container and into the No. 2 cargo hold.     On January 30, 2012, at 1900 hours, the cargo hatches were closed and ventilated.  A marine chemist was contacted and boarded the vessel at 0800 hours on January 31, 2012.  The vapors showed a concentration of 42 PPM in the No. 2 cargo hold.  The master sent all crew members to undergo toxicology screening at a local clinic.  All crew members tested negative for exposure.      On January 31, 2012, at 1800 hours, OMI completed clean up operations and on February 1, 2012, at 0800 hours the marine chemist returned to the vessel, re-tested the vapor concentration of the No. 2 cargo hold, and cleared the hold for loading.    Loading re-commenced at 1300 hours on February 1, 2012, and the FLINTERMAR sailed for foreign waters at 0100 hours on February 2, 2012.

column168: David (Driver) pulled in to position to unload product into the FedEx tanks, connected the hoses to his pump and to the tanks and proceeded to unload his product. During the unloading process the cap on the opposite side of the pump came off and fuel was released in the parking lot for approximately 45-60 seconds at which time the pump was shutoff and the belly valves closed.    Upon inspection of the cap it was clear that the although the cap was secured with cable to prevent it from opening, the ears used to secure the cap had broken and caused the malfunction.
column169: To prevent future similar releases, we have added weekly thorough inspections of all caps and ears by our in house mechanics. We have also added an additional Velcro strap specifically made for this application to all of our pump caps in addition to the cables we normally use to secure the ears from unintentionally opening.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.  THIS WAS SIMPLY A MATTER OF LIQUID WASTE WITH PH BELOW 12.5 BEING SHIPPED AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE ON 006754352JJK-14.  PH DISCREPANCY WAS NOTED BY LAB ON 01/13/2012.  I CONTACTED TVA ON 01/13/2012.  TVA GAVE PERMISSION TO MOVE DRUM TO LINE 15 OF MANIFEST, CHANGE PROFILE TO CE1026 FOR THIS DRUM, ADD PROPER DOT SHIPPING NAME AND DOO2 WASTE CODE ON 01/17/2012.  PER LINDA STEWART, SOURCE WAS CHLORIDE BLEACH.  THIS COMPOUND IS LISTED UNDER ALTERNATIVE PROFILE, SO DISCREPANCY WAS RESOLVED.

column168: DRIVER WAS PRESSURING THE TRAILER UP WITH AIR IN AN ATTEMPT TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. WHILE THE TRAILER WAS PRESSURING UP, DRIVER HEARD A LOUD POP AND PRODUCT BEGAN SPRAYING FROM A HOLE THAT DEVELOPED ON THE STREETSIDE OF THE TANK. DRIVER SHUT OFF THE AIR SUPPLY AND NOTIFIED THE OPERATOR OF AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE. THE SAGINAW FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED AND PLUGGED THE HOLE. THE RELEASE LASTED APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS BEFORE THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED. THE TANK LOST 1,009 GALLONS OF ACID. THE ACID WAS CONTAINED ON THE PLANT PROPERTY AND CLEANED UP BY SWS ENVIRONMENTAL. A SMALL CABINET SHOP WITH 4 EMPLOYEES NEXT DOOR TO THIS PROPERTY WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION FOR TWO HOURS. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF INTO THE RECEIVING TANK. THE TANK HAD A CHEMLINE LINER THAT WAS INSTALLED 9-22-11. THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE LINING ON THE STREET SIDE OF THE TRAILER JUST ABOVE THE HOSE TRAY TWO THIRDS BACK FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. DUE TO THE DEFECT IN THE LINING, THE ACID CORRODED THE TANK SHELL CAUSING A 1/4 INCH HOLE. IT IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME WHAT CAUSED THE DAMAGE TO THE TANK LINING.
column169: THIS TRAILER HAD JUST COMPLETED ALL CARGO TANK INSPECTIONS 9-22-11, INCLUDING A NEW LINER BEING INSTALLED. MARTIN WILL HAVE ALL LINED TANKS FROM THIS REPAIR FACILITY REINSPECTED INTERNALLY.

column168: Driver reported that he had four, 20-ft lengths of hose on truck and needed one more length to reach customer hook up.  Customer provided the extra hose. Driver had placed velcro straps at each of his hose connections to secure cam locks in place.  When his hoses would not reach, he located customer to report issue.  Customer retrieved a section of hose and brought it to driver who connected to his hose and customer hook up.  He failed to secure the cam locks on customer hose with velcro.  During the unloading process, a customer hose cam lock came loose, allowing the hose section to separate and release product.  Process was quickly shut down.  Some product was released under pressure before pump was stopped, and further product that remained in hose after shut down was released until hose connection could be secured.  Customer provided emergency response on their property and declined offer of clean up from carrier.
column169: Drivers have been issued additional velcro for use in situations requiring the use of equipment other than that carried on the driver's unit.  Drivers were also reminded that the use of customer equipment is considered a "non-routine task" and as such requires a heightened awareness to ensure safe unloading / loading of product.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: Kansas City Southern Railroad (KCS) personnel observed dripping from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) on car GATX 28331 at approximately 1330 hrs on January 28, 2012. Call in from Critical Incident Desk (CID) Dennis Goad stated that the loaded tank car is dripping product from the bottom outlet valve at approx 1 drip per 10-15 seconds. The CID notified Steve McNealy of KCS and Mr. McNealy requested United States Environmental Services LLC (USES) respond to investigate and perform corrective actions on the railcar. Mr. Jason Nevills of USES responded to the request and was dispatched with equipment and personnel to the site.    Southern Ionics Inc. (shipper) sent response personnel to the site as well. USES coordinated with Southern Ionics Inc. to develop plan of action to be taken. USES and crew arrived on-site at 1530 hours CST and performed a site safety briefing. Upon arriving onsite USES personnel were informed by Southern Ionics Inc. that the leak was from the unloading assembly on the BOV.     It was determined that the unloading assembly had an auxillary loading appurtenance that was left on the BOV and that the appurtenance was DOT non-compliant. The auxillary appurtenance is utilized in the loading and un-loading of material and is not fit for travel.  The auxillary appurtenance was removed and it was observed that the unloading assembly was leaking from the internal plunger spring which was defective. The defective spring and plunger were replaced with new parts. Upon re-installing the assembly no leakage was visible or detected.     USES then checked the man-way area of the railcar and found all the plugs and fittings were tight and secure. USES personnel then secured the car. Upon completion of the investigation and corrective actions performed USES informed Mr. McNealy that the job was complete.     *File Note Item 19 - the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     *File Note Item 27 - Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to the carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.     *The delay of the submittal of this 5800 form is partly due to the fact that KCS discovered that more than just this car in the shipper's fleet contained the DOT non-complaint "quick-connect" appurtenance and KCS continued to work with the shipper to assure that all of the auxillary appurtenances were removed before any further shipment.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING LPG FROM OUR LPG TANKER TO ONE OF OUR LPG NURSE TANKS OUR OPERATOR HEARD AN UNFAMILIAR SOUND AND LOOKED BACK AT HIS TANKER TO SEE A VAPOR CLOUD FORMING AROUND THE TANKER AND TRUCK TRACTOR. AT ALMOST THE SAME TIME HE HEARD THE ENGINE OF HIS TRUCK TRACTOR BEGINNING TO "RUN-A-WAY" WHICH IS A PROCESS THAT OCCURS WHEN A FUEL IS DISPERSED FROM THE ATMOSPHERE INTO THE AIR INTAKE OF THE ENGINE. THIS WAS THE PROPANE GAS VAPOR THAT ESCAPED DUE TO A PREMATURE MALFUNCTION & RUPTURE OF A HOSE THAT WAS WRAPPED IN A STAINLESS STEEL BRAID ALLOWING THE PROPANE TO ESCAPE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THESE VAPORS WERE ABLE TO FIND AN IGNITION SOURCE RESULTING IN A FLASH FIRE OF THE VAPORS.   *A MORE DETAILED NARRATIVE OF THIS INCIDENT CAN BE FOUND IN THE STATE OF LOUISIANA STATE POLICE INCIDENT REPORT #12-00179
column169: AS A RESULT OF OUR INVESTIGATIVE PROCESS OF THIS INCIDENT WE HAVE CONCLUDED THAT THE PRIMARY FACTOR IN THIS INCIDENT WAS A PREMATURE MALFUNCTION OF A RELATIVELY NEW HOSE THAT HAS SINCE BEEN FOUND TO HAVE FAILED AND RUPTURED ALLOWING PROPANE TO BE RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. OUR RESEARCH HAS LED US TO SEEK ADVISE OF ANOTHER MANUFACTURER OF SIMILAR HOSES AND WE NOW USE A DIFFERENT HOSE/PIPING TO MAKE THIS CONNECTION IN ORDER TO LESSEN THE HAZARD OF LEAKING PROPANE POSSIBILITIES.

column168: Memo to the file re jan 6 2012 release at Duffy’s bulk plant  I took a call from Barb at the Duffy office at about 115pm, informing me that Noonan Transportation, our contract hauler, had experienced a small spill at the Duffy location.  I left the Proctor office immediately for Duffy’s.    Upon arrival I met Terry, the Branch Manager for Noonan out of West Rutland, VT, and the driver of the transport, John.  Terry explained that one of their 4-inch transport hoses had failed, causing a discharge of fuel oil to the interior of the concrete containment pad.   The failure caused spray to the interior of the dike, as well as to the exterior of the dike beyond the containment area.   Terry estimated total discharge of approximately 10 gallons.  Based upon my observations, I concurred with Terry’s assessment of volume.   Although the majority of the discharged fuel had been contained by the containment concrete pad, when I arrived, Noonan had already placed approximately 20 square feet of sorbent on the ground outside the containment area where the fuel had gathered from the spray of the broken hose.  The ground was frozen solid, it had snowed about an inch that morning, and the sorbent appeared to have soaked up the free product that had hit the ground outside the containment area.   Given the frozen state of the ground, it was clear that little of the free product outside the containment area had been absorbed by the ground; rather it remained on the surface of the frozen soil.  Beyond the 20 square foot area affected outside the containment area, the snow was slightly pink in color from the spray, but there was no free product beyond the 20 square foot area.  Terry informed me that he had already called the State of Vermont Spill hotline and that Clean Harbors, that Noonan’s environmental firm had been called, and that Clean Harbors was on their way.  I considered the discharge to be under control and already contained by Noonan’s people when I arrived on site.  I called the State of Vermont, spoke to Tim, at 230pm and reported the discharge.  I also called the National Response Center and reported the discharge (report # 999769) and shortly thereafter called Bill of HOP and recounted the description above.  Bill gave me an incident number, which I recorded as #10606  Over the course of the afternoon, I re-visited the site 3 more times and visited with Terry to make sure nothing had changed.  On my last visit, sometime around 530p, Terry was still on site, and a Clean Harbors staff person was on site, using an iron bar to chip away the top layer of frozen solid where the free product had gathered outside the containment area.   Clean Harbors already had a waste containment drum on site and had already placed a portion of affected soil into the waste drum.
